#C++ Code
class Solution {
public:
    void merge(vector<int>& nums1, int m, vector<int>& nums2, int n) {
        int p1 = m-1, p2 = m+n-1, p3 = n-1;
        while(p3>=0){
            if(p1>=0 && nums2[p3]<nums1[p1]){
                nums1[p2] = nums1[p1];
                p1--,p2--;
            }
            else{
                nums1[p2] = nums2[p3];
                p3--;
                p2--;
            }
        }
    }
};

"Idea:
  1) Three pointer approach and condition where we iterate whole p3
  The main idea is to merge the arrays from the back side instead of the front.
Since nums1 already has extra space at the end, we use three pointers:

p1 for the last valid element in nums1
p3 for the last element in nums2
p2 for the final position in merged array

We compare the largest remaining elements of both arrays and place the bigger one at p2."

Time Complexity:- O(m+n)             Space complexity:- O(1)
